Level 2: Datatypes & Character Basics

Problem 3: Character Case Shifter
Goal: Explore how char types interact with integers using ASCII values.
Input: Read a single lowercase letter from the user (char).
Task: Subtract 32 from the character value to convert it to uppercase.
Output: Print both the original character and its new uppercase counterpart.



CODE:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h> 
int main() {
    char ch;

    printf("Enter a single lowercase letter: ");
    if (scanf(" %c", &ch) != 1) {  
        printf("Invalid input.\n");
        return 1;
    }

    
    if (islower(ch)) {
        char upper = ch - 32;  // ASCII: 'a' (97) - 32 = 'A' (65)
        printf("Original character: %c\n", ch);
        printf("Uppercase character: %c\n", upper);
    } else {
        printf("Error: Please enter a lowercase letter (a-z).\n");
    }

    return 0;
}


OUTPUT:


Enter a single lowercase letter: j
Original character: j
Uppercase character: J



